# 📄 DIGITAL LITERACY PROJECT REPORT


## 📌 Introduction (100–150 words)

In today’s digital world, having basic digital literacy skills is essential for students. As a Student Digital Ambassador, my role was to create awareness about safe and effective use of digital tools among my peers. This project helped me understand various aspects of digital literacy such as online communication, professional presence, collaboration tools, and cyber safety.

Through this project, I completed five tasks that involved creating an infographic, building a digital portfolio, exploring coding and collaboration platforms, writing professional emails, and studying cybercrime. Each task contributed to improving my knowledge and practical skills. This report summarizes my work, learnings, and experiences from each module of the course.


## 🎨 Task 1: Digital Literacy Infographic (150–200 words)

For this task, I used Canva to design a digital literacy awareness infographic. The infographic focused on explaining what digital literacy is, safe internet practices, and the importance of maintaining a professional online presence. I included simple visuals, icons, and short points to make the content easy to understand for students.

The design highlighted key concepts such as protecting personal information, using strong passwords, and being responsible on social media. I also added examples of useful digital tools like Google Workspace and GitHub.

One challenge I faced was selecting the right layout and balancing text with visuals. However, I found it interesting to use design tools creatively to present information in a clear and attractive way. This task helped me understand how visual communication can effectively spread awareness among students.


## 💼 Task 2: Digital Portfolio (150–200 words)

In this task, I created and updated my profiles on platforms like GitHub, LinkedIn, and Kaggle. These platforms are important for building a professional digital presence. GitHub is used for showcasing coding projects, LinkedIn is used for networking and career opportunities, and Kaggle is used for data science practice.

I created a GitHub profile README including my basic details and learning goals. On LinkedIn, I added my education details such as my degree and university. These platforms will help me build my profile over the next four years by adding projects, achievements, and skills.

This task helped me understand the importance of maintaining a professional online identity. In the future, I plan to regularly update my profiles and use them to connect with professionals, apply for internships, and showcase my work.


## 💻 Task 3: Platforms Exploration (150–200 words)

For this task, I explored both coding and collaboration platforms. I completed a beginner-level coding challenge on HackerRank, which helped me understand basic problem-solving and programming concepts. It was a good starting point for improving my coding skills.

In addition, I created a Google Form with five questions related to digital literacy awareness. The form included multiple-choice and short-answer questions. I also viewed responses through Google Sheets, which showed how data can be collected and analyzed easily.

This task helped me learn how online platforms can support both learning and collaboration. Coding platforms improve logical thinking, while tools like Google Forms help in organizing and collecting information efficiently. These skills will be useful for academic projects and teamwork in the future.


## 📧 Task 4: Email Etiquette & Communication (100–150 words)

In this task, I wrote two professional emails—one requesting an assignment extension and another applying for a summer internship. This helped me understand the importance of proper email structure, including subject lines, greetings, clear content, and formal closing.

A common issue in digital communication is misunderstanding due to unclear or informal messages. For example, a student sending a rude or incomplete email to a professor may not receive a response. This problem can be avoided by using polite language, proper formatting, and clear communication.

Overall, this task improved my ability to communicate professionally and responsibly in academic and professional environments.


## 🔐 Task 5: Cybercrime Awareness (100–150 words)

While working on the cybercrime case study, I learned about phishing attacks and how easily people can become victims. What surprised me most was how attackers create fake websites and messages that look very real, making it difficult to identify scams.

One important habit I will change is being more cautious before clicking on links or sharing personal information online. I will always verify sources and ensure that websites are secure before entering any details.

This task increased my awareness about online threats and taught me practical steps to stay safe in the digital world.



## ✅ Conclusion (100 words)

This Digital Literacy project helped me gain important knowledge and practical skills required in today’s digital environment. I learned how to use digital tools effectively, communicate professionally, and stay safe online. Each task contributed to improving my understanding of responsible digital behavior.

As a Student Digital Ambassador, I now feel more confident in guiding others about digital literacy. These skills will not only help me in my academic journey but also in my future career. Overall, this project was a valuable learning experience.


